# ◆ RAG Evaluation System


> Project 8 of my RAG Mastery Journey — The Final Project

An automated evaluation system that measures RAG quality 
objectively across three metrics: faithfulness, answer 
relevance, and context precision. No more guessing if your 
RAG system is good — now you have numbers.

---

##  Live Results

### Overall Scores — 10 Questions Evaluated

![Dashboard Overview](screenshots/dashboard_overview.png)

| Metric | Score |
|---|---|
| **Overall** | 0.710 |
| **Faithfulness** | 1.000 |
| **Answer Relevance** | 0.900 |
| **Context Precision** | 0.230 |

> **Key finding:** The system never hallucinates 
> (faithfulness = 1.0) and almost always addresses 
> the question (relevance = 0.9). The weak point is 
> context precision (0.23) — retrieved chunks contain 
> noise. This tells us exactly where to improve: 
> better chunking or higher similarity thresholds.

---

### Score Distribution & Metrics Comparison

![Score Distribution](screenshots/score_distribution.png)

Most questions score between 0.67 and 0.83. 
The distribution shows a consistent system — 
no random failures, predictable quality.

---

### Per-Document Performance

![Per Document](screenshots/per_document.png)

Japan culture document scores 0.71 overall across 
10 questions. Running with all 3 documents would 
show comparative performance per knowledge base.

---

### Score Trend Across All Questions

![Score Trend](screenshots/score_trend.png)

Faithfulness (blue) stays flat at 1.0 — the system 
never hallucinates regardless of question difficulty.
Overall score (red) trends upward as questions get 
easier to answer from context.
Context Precision (pink) is the most variable metric —
some questions retrieve perfectly relevant chunks, 
others retrieve noisy chunks.

---

### Question-Level Results Table

![Results Table](screenshots/results_table.png)

Every question scored individually. Faithfulness = 1.0 
across all questions. Context precision is the 
differentiator — questions with 0.5 precision score 
0.83 overall, questions with 0.0 precision score 0.67.

---

### Best and Worst Questions + Latency

![Best Worst](screenshots/best_worst.png)

| | Score | Question |
|---|---|---|
|  Best | 0.83 | Ancestry percentage from Jōmon people |
|  Worst | 0.33 | What year did Japan adopt kanji from China? |

**Latency:** Average 2105ms · Fastest 652ms · Slowest 8133ms

The worst question (kanji adoption year) scored low 
because it asks for a specific date — the retrieved 
chunks contained the topic but not the exact year, 
causing low context precision and answer relevance.

---

##  What This System Measures

### Faithfulness (1.000)
Does the answer use ONLY the retrieved context?
A score of 1.0 means zero hallucination across all 
10 questions. The grounding prompt works perfectly.

### Answer Relevance (0.900)
Does the answer actually address the question?
0.9 means 9 out of 10 questions were directly answered.
The one miss was a specific date question where context 
lacked the exact information needed.

### Context Precision (0.230)
Of the retrieved chunks, how many were actually useful?
0.23 is the clear weak point. With top_k=3, many 
retrieved chunks were tangentially related but not 
directly used in the answer. Fix: increase similarity 
threshold or reduce top_k to 2.

---

##  Architecture
```
testset.py    → generate Q&A pairs from documents
metrics.py    → faithfulness, relevance, precision
benchmark.py  → run evaluation across all questions  
dashboard.py  → Streamlit visualization
```

---

##  Key Concepts Learned

| Concept | What it means |
|---|---|
| LLM-as-judge | Use LLM to score answers objectively |
| Faithfulness | Zero hallucination = 1.0 |
| Answer relevance | Did you answer what was asked? |
| Context precision | Was your retrieval focused or noisy? |
| Test set generation | Documents write their own test cases |
| Benchmark | 30 questions, objective scores, no guessing |
| Evaluation loop | RAG pipeline → score → improve → repeat |

---

##  What The Results Tell You
```
Faithfulness 1.00  → Grounding prompt works perfectly
Relevance    0.90  → Agent answers the right question
Precision    0.23  → Retrieval is noisy — top_k too high

Fix: reduce top_k from 3 to 2
     increase min_similarity from 0.35 to 0.45
     Expected improvement: precision 0.23 → 0.45+
```

This is the value of evaluation — you don't guess what 
to fix. The numbers tell you exactly where the system 
is weak and what to change.

---

##  Run Locally
```bash
git clone https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/rag-eval.git
cd rag-eval
python -m venv venv
venv\Scripts\activate
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

Add `.env`:
```
GROQ_API_KEY=your-groq-key-here
```
```bash
# Step 1 — Index documents
python ingest.py

# Step 2 — Generate test questions
python testset.py

# Step 3 — Run benchmark
python benchmark.py

# Step 4 — View dashboard
streamlit run dashboard.py
```

